1. Use comments: Insert comments in your code to explain the purpose of each function, class, and section of code. Comments can be written using // for single-line comments or /*...*/ for multi-line comments.

Example:

```
// This function calculates the sum of two numbers.
function calculateSum(num1, num2) {
    return num1 + num2;
}
```

2. Update the function signatures: Provide clear and concise descriptions within function signatures, including parameters and return values. This helps other developers understand how to use the function correctly.

Example:

```
/**
 * Calculates the sum of two numbers.
 * @param {number} num1 - The first number.
 * @param {number} num2 - The second number.
 * @returns {number} - The sum of num1 and num2.
 */
function calculateSum(num1, num2) {
    return num1 + num2;
}
```

3. Document complex logic: Use comments to explain any complex or non-obvious logic within your code. This can help other developers understand your intentions and avoid confusion.

Example:

```
// Check if the given number is even.
// A number is even if it is divisible by 2 with no remainder.
if (number % 2 === 0) {
    isEven = true;
} else {
   isEven = false;
}
```

